[1]
Date: Wed 8 Aug 2001
From: Dawn Wesson <wesson@tulane.edu>
Source: State of Louisiana, Office of Public Health, 8 Aug 2001 [edited]

Eastern Equine Encephalitis and La Crosse Encephalitis in Louisiana
------------------------------------------------------------------
Two horses have been diagnosed with Eastern Equine Encephalitis in
Louisiana, one in Bienville parish and one in Webster parish. Both parishes
are in the northwestern portion of the state.
Bienville Parish: 6 year old mare, unvaccinated
Alphavirus positive - IgM 1:4096, IgG 1:64
Onset - 7/11/01
Collection - 7/11/01
Euthanized - 7/12/01
Webster Parish: 8 year old mare, unvaccinated
Alphavirus positive - IgM 1:4096, IgG 1:256
Onset - 7/28/01
Collection - 7/28/01
Died - 7/28/01
A 7 year old boy from Allen parish in west-central Louisiana has been
diagnosed with La Crosse encephalitis and is recovering. The patient also
visited a site in nearby Vernon parish within 14 days of onset.
_Ochlerotatus triseriatus_ and _Aedes albopictus_ were collected from both
areas and are being tested for virus.
Bunyavirus positive by indirect IFA: IgM 1:1024, IgG 1:16
(presumed to be La Crosse virus)
Onset - 7/25/01
Report - 8/2/01
The 2 most recent human La Crosse encephalitis cases in Louisiana were in
1995 and 1996 in Lafourche and Calcasieu parishes, respectively.
--
Dawn M. Wesson, Ph.D.
Associate Professor
Department of Tropical Medicine
Tulane School of Public Health
